  "Make larger verbs out of multiple words": [
   {
    "text": "In English, you have one simple verb like \"eat,\" and then you can add other words to form larger ideas like \"he made someone eat,\" or \"he was eaten,\" etc, whereas in Hebrew and Aramaic, all of these permutations will be entirely different one-word verbs with similar spellings because they are formed from the same ",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "text": "shoresh",
    "type": "global",
    "tokens": [
     {
      "text": "shoresh",
      "type": "text"
     }
    ],
    "targetSubtopic": "Shoresh",
    "targetTopic": "Shoresh",
    "enclosingTopic": "Binyan",
    "enclosingSubtopic": "Make larger verbs out of multiple words"
   },
   {
    "text": " root.",
    "type": "text"
   }
  ],
  "Use entirely separate words for related concepts": [
   {
    "text": "In English, words that have related meanings do not necessarily look similar. For example, you might have verbs like \"buy\" and \"sell\" that have related meanings but no visual similarity, whereas in Hebrew and Aramaic, a word like \"to buy\" (לִקְנוֹת) and word like \"to sell\" (לְהִיקָּנוֹת) would be verbs formed from two different binyans of the same ",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "text": "shoresh",
    "type": "global",
    "tokens": [
     {
      "text": "shoresh",
      "type": "text"
     }
    ],
    "targetSubtopic": "Shoresh",
    "targetTopic": "Shoresh",
    "enclosingTopic": "Binyan",
    "enclosingSubtopic": "Use entirely separate words for related concepts"
   },
   {
    "text": " קנה, and so will have a similar spelling.",
    "type": "text"
   }
  ],
